Health Care Service Corporation (HCSC) operates Blue Cross and Blue Shield® Plans in Illinois, Montana, New Mexico, Oklahoma and Texas and is the fourth-largest health insurer in the U.S. Founded in 1936, we serve nearly 16 million members across five states and employ nearly 23,000 people in over 60 local offices. Everything we do at HCSC is guided by a straightforward core purpose: “To do everything in our power to stand with our members in sickness and in health.”
The Senior Analytics Consultant analyzes complex business problems and issues using data from internal and external sources to provide insight to internal decision-makers. This position involves collaboration with several business areas including actuarial and provider network. This team is part of our Provider Analytics division and produces data for CEO dashboards and upper management reporting. The ideal candidate will have strong analytical and technical skills as well as strong business acumen with knowledge of the healthcare insurance industry and experience working with claims data.
BASIC FUNCTIONCreates specifications for reports and analysis based on business  needs and required or available data elements. May provide consultation to users and lead cross-functional teams to address business issues. Produces datasets and reports for analysis using system reporting tools. May perform research and assists in analyzing financial and health data, including medical algorithms to determine health care expenditures, medical and economic outcomes, and cost containment strategies. Identifies and interprets trends and patterns in datasets to locate influences.
JOB REQUIREMENTS

Bachelor Degree and 5 years' experience in health care data statistical analysis OR 7 years experience in healthcare data statistical analysis.
3 years experience in data analysis and information reporting relating to healthcare data;
Ability to query and analyze large sets of complex healthcare data and 4 years experience using Structured Query Language (SQL);
Ability to derive insights from complex data for presentation and decision making;
Experience with data visualization tools Tableau, MicroStategy or similar;.
Demonstrated best practices and knowledge of internal or external business issues to improve products or services;
Ability to independently solve complex problems;
Ability to work independently with minimal guidance;
Ability to serve as a resource for colleagues with less experience; may direct the work of other staff members.

PREFERRED REQUIREMENTSPreference will be given to applicants with the following skills, experience, education, or knowledge:

Bachelor Degree;
Experience authoring/maintaining SAS for complex reporting purposes;
Experience or exposure to clinical data integration;
Ability to provide subject matter expertise on healthcare/insurance industry; 
Expertise in business analysis – process flows, facilitation, requirements gathering, testing software systems, etc.;
Proficient creating and leveraging complex pivot tables;
Financial analysis related to provider and facility data;

Apply for this job (HS-1008708) or view what else we have available at at hcsc.com/careers
Relocation will not be provided for this position.
Sponsorship will not be provided for this position.
We are an Equal Opportunity Employment / Affirmative Action employer dedicated to workforce diversity and a drug-free and smoke-free workplace. Drug screening and background investigation are required, as allowed by law. All qualified applicants will receive consideration for employment without regard to race, color, religion, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, national origin, disability, or protected veteran status.

The Chief Research Methodologist on Data Collection will have principal responsibility for leading and transforming the RAND American Life Panel (ALP), a nationally-representative panel of approximately 6,000 Americans who have agreed to take regular online surveys on a variety of research topics.  The position will also take the lead on other panels developed at RAND such as the American Educators Panel, and the American Veterans Panel, as well as other surveys programmed and hosted using RAND’s Multimode Interviewing Capability (MMIC) survey software.  This is an exciting opportunity for an individual with survey research methodology expertise and interest in leading an innovative research portfolio that expands the frontier of the panel survey research field. At the helm of multiple, high profile, high quality national surveys at RAND, the Chief Research Methodologist will disseminate findings to leading media outlets and to policy makers.  
Responsibilities include:

Provide strategic oversight of survey projects and hosting operations, including supervising staff responsible for implementation and quality assurance activities;
Actively participate in research as PI, co-PI, or team member on research projects, with a particular focus on survey methodology topics;
Provide leadership and technical advice on statistical and methodological issues for internal and external clients and researchers;
Consult on survey design, including sampling and questionnaire design;
Oversee sample integrity and provide sample weighting advice; design experiments;
Analyze data collected during pretests or methodological components of ongoing studies;
Author sections of technical reports, methodology reports, and other document deliverables;
Monitor survey participation and oversee panel member retention efforts;
Prepare or review deliverables, communicating with the client and subcontractor(s) about project requirements, and developing financial business plans related to data collection; 
Interface with external stakeholders such as media outlets to disseminate findings on special survey projects.
Publish journal articles to advance RAND’s contribution to science and to contribute to the field of survey research

Qualifications 

Strong quantitative capability, especially in quantitative survey methodologies
Strong leadership and interpersonal skills, able to work with multiple stakeholders
Significant experience in large scale survey operations, preferably in a management position
Demonstrated ability to secure funding
Demonstrated ability to be flexible, creative, and innovative
Experience with institutional review board regulations and processes
Excellent verbal and written communication skills

Education Requirements: Ph.D. in survey methodology, statistics, sociology, demography, economics, or related discipline is required
Experience: Prefer 7 years of experience, with 3 years of leadership experience, though will consider exceptional candidates with fewer years of experience
Security Clearance: Must be able to obtain a security clearance
Location: Santa Monica, CA 
RAND is an Equal Opportunity Employer Minorities/Females/Vets/Disabled

Build and inspire innovative, cutting edge technology in a newly created role;
Brilliant North Sydney location;
Company culture of opportunity and achievement;
Fantastic employee incentive program.

The CompanyIn just over four years, Pepper has transformed itself from a Company of 80 employees in Sydney to an 1800-strong force across Australia, Asia and Europe. Pepper’s success is due largely to its innovative product range which has been custom-made to fulfil the needs of customers. The Company has continued its focus on innovation with the recent launch of its innovation centre, commonly referred to as PIC, established to capitalise on new design techniques and emerging trends and technologies to build unique customer experiences across channel, product and service delivery. The initial success of PIC has emanated in an opportunity for an experienced and passionate data scientist to apply their specialist knowledge to assist the PIC team achieve success.
The RoleThe purpose of the Innovation Portfolio Manager – Data Science role is to manage a portfolio of Pepper’s innovation initiatives through the stages of the Innovation process collaboratively within the team, the business, and external customers. The Innovation Portfolio Manager will also be expected to contribute their specialist knowledge in the field of Data Science to the team to help them achieve success with their portfolios. The Innovation Centre has a focus on delivering innovation through our process to ensure that value is created by meeting unmet customer needs in a new way to Pepper.
Through the use of Human Centred Design, the Innovation Portfolio Manager will be responsible for developing initiatives and understanding their value to both customers and Pepper. As they progress initiatives through the process it is expected that the desirability, feasibility, and viability of initiatives are assessed and the initiatives of greatest value are progressed whilst initiatives of little or no value are not. It is the responsibility of the Innovation Portfolio Manager to advocate, based on research, the initiatives to progress and those which are not to progress.
The PersonPepper is interested in candidates who love a challenge and want to leave a meaningful impact on the Company. Candidates must have thorough quantitative and qualitative research experience and possess a strong ability to work independently and proactively initiate projects. A working knowledge of statistical programming, Big Data concepts, expert problem-solving and data-analysis skills are essential. It is expected that the candidate has strong problem solving and strategic thinking abilities and at least 12 months experience in a similar role. It is highly advantageous to come from a consulting or customer strategy background.
Why Pepper?Pepper’s environment is suitable for a team player seeking change and career progression.In addition to this, Pepper:

Promotes well-being by providing free gym membership, access to a first-class EAP and encouraging all team members to embrace a work-life balance;
Provides outstanding online training and development opportunities;
Grants team members access to the Company’s paid parental leave, home loan and car loan programs; and
Allows team members to apply for up to 6 weeks annual leave each year.

